---
export const prerender = true;

import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import MermaidDiagram from '@components/MermaidDiagram.astro';
import Callout from '@components/Callout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Architecture — SWE-Squad">
  <div class="page">

    <a href="/" class="back-link">&larr; Home</a>

    <h1 class="page-title">Architecture</h1>
    <p class="page-intro">A deep dive into the SWE-Squad pipeline, feedback loops, memory system, and provider architecture.</p>

    <!-- Section 1: Full Pipeline Diagram -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Full Pipeline</h2>
      <p>SWE-Squad automates the entire incident lifecycle through a five-stage pipeline. Each stage contains focused sub-steps that handle a specific concern, from raw log ingestion all the way to validated deployment.</p>

      <div class="diagram-container">
        <MermaidDiagram code={`flowchart TD
    subgraph Monitor["🔍 Monitor"]
        M1[Log Ingestion]
        M2[Pattern Detection]
        M3[Alert Generation]
    end
    subgraph Triage["⚖️ Triage"]
        T1[Severity Classification]
        T2[Deduplication]
        T3[Assignment]
    end
    subgraph Investigate["🔬 Investigate"]
        I1[Codebase Exploration]
        I2[Root Cause Analysis]
        I3[Context Assembly]
    end
    subgraph Fix["🔧 Fix"]
        F1[Code Generation]
        F2[Test Generation]
        F3[Self-Review]
    end
    subgraph Gate["🛡️ Stability Gate"]
        G1[Unit Tests]
        G2[Lint & Type Check]
        G3[Security Scan]
        G4[Smoke Tests]
    end
    Monitor --> Triage --> Investigate --> Fix --> Gate
    Gate -- Pass --> Deploy[🚀 Deploy]
    Gate -- Fail --> Investigate`} />
      </div>

      <div class="stage-descriptions">
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Monitor</strong> — Ingests logs and metrics from production systems, detects anomalous patterns, and generates structured alerts for downstream processing.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Triage</strong> — Classifies each alert by severity, deduplicates recurring issues to avoid duplicate work, and assigns the incident to the appropriate AI agent.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Investigate</strong> — Explores the relevant codebase, performs root-cause analysis, and assembles the context needed to produce an accurate fix.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Fix</strong> — Generates targeted code patches, produces corresponding tests, and runs a self-review step to catch obvious issues before validation.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Stability Gate</strong> — Validates the proposed fix through unit tests, linting, type checking, security scanning, and smoke tests. Only fixes that pass all checks proceed to deployment.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 2: Fix Loop Diagram -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Fix Loop</h2>
      <p>When the Stability Gate rejects a fix, the system does not give up. Instead, it enters an iterative feedback loop: the agent reviews the specific failures, adjusts its approach, and generates an improved patch.</p>

      <div class="diagram-container">
        <MermaidDiagram code={`flowchart LR
    Fix --> Gate[Stability Gate]
    Gate -- Pass --> Deploy
    Gate -- Fail --> Review[Review Failures]
    Review --> Adjust[Adjust Approach]
    Adjust --> Fix`} />
      </div>

      <p>The loop is bounded by a retry limit. After a maximum of three attempts, the system escalates the incident to a human engineer along with the full diagnostic trace, ensuring no issue is silently abandoned. Each retry carries forward the failure context so the agent avoids repeating the same mistake.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 3: Semantic Memory Flow -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Semantic Memory</h2>
      <p>SWE-Squad maintains a semantic memory store that accumulates knowledge across incidents. Every incoming issue is matched against this store to surface relevant historical context before the agent begins work.</p>

      <div class="diagram-container">
        <MermaidDiagram code={`flowchart TD
    Input[Incoming Issue] --> Memory[Semantic Memory Store]
    Memory --> |Relevant Context| Agent[AI Agent]
    Agent --> |New Findings| Memory
    Memory --> |Lessons Learned| Knowledge[Knowledge Base]
    Knowledge --> |Historical Patterns| Memory`} />
      </div>

      <p>As agents investigate and resolve issues, they write new findings back into the memory store. Over time, these findings are distilled into a persistent knowledge base of lessons learned and recurring patterns. This means the system becomes progressively faster and more accurate: previously seen error signatures are recognized immediately, and the agent can skip redundant exploration steps.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 4: Provider Plugin Architecture -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Provider Plugin Architecture</h2>
      <p>SWE-Squad isolates model-specific logic behind a provider interface. The <code>BaseProvider</code> abstract class defines the contract every provider must satisfy, while the <code>ProviderRegistry</code> manages registration and lookup at runtime.</p>

      <div class="diagram-container">
        <MermaidDiagram code={`flowchart TD
    subgraph Interface["Provider Interface"]
        PI[BaseProvider]
        PM[ProviderRegistry]
    end
    subgraph Implementations["Provider Implementations"]
        P1[OpenAIProvider]
        P2[AnthropicProvider]
        P3[LocalProvider]
        P4[CustomProvider]
    end
    PI --> P1
    PI --> P2
    PI --> P3
    PI --> P4
    PM --> PI`} />
      </div>

      <p>Each concrete provider — OpenAI, Anthropic, a local model server, or a custom implementation — extends <code>BaseProvider</code> and implements the same set of methods. Because the core pipeline depends only on the abstract interface, swapping or adding providers requires no changes to the surrounding logic. Teams can plug in new models, swap backends, or run entirely local inference without touching the pipeline code.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 5: Agent Roles & Decision Logic -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Agent Roles</h2>
      <p>SWE-Squad deploys specialized agents at each pipeline stage. Each agent has a defined role, specific inputs and outputs, and decision logic that governs its behavior.</p>

      <div class="diagram-container">
        <MermaidDiagram code={`flowchart TD
    subgraph Agents["Pipeline Agents"]
        Monitor["🔍 Monitor Agent"]
        Triage["⚖️ Triage Agent"]
        Investigator["🔬 Investigator Agent"]
        Developer["🔧 Developer Agent"]
        Ralph["🛡️ Ralph Wiggum<br/>(Stability Gate)"]
        Creative["💡 Creative Agent"]
        Distiller["🧠 Distiller Agent"]
    end
    Monitor -->|"Alert"| Triage
    Triage -->|"Classified Incident"| Investigator
    Investigator -->|"Root Cause + Context"| Developer
    Developer -->|"Patch + Tests"| Ralph
    Ralph -->|"Validated Fix"| Distiller
    Creative -->|"Alternative Approaches"| Developer
    Distiller -->|"Lessons Learned"| Memory["Semantic Memory"]`} />
      </div>

      <div class="stage-descriptions">
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Monitor Agent</strong> — Continuously ingests logs, metrics, and error signals from production systems. <em>Inputs:</em> raw log streams, metric thresholds, alert rules. <em>Outputs:</em> structured alerts with severity hints. <em>Decision logic:</em> anomaly detection via pattern matching against known signatures and statistical baselines.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Triage Agent</strong> — Classifies each alert by severity and deduplicates against active incidents. <em>Inputs:</em> structured alerts from Monitor. <em>Outputs:</em> classified, deduplicated incident tickets. <em>Decision logic:</em> severity scored by error category, blast radius, and user impact; duplicates detected via semantic similarity against open tickets.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Investigator Agent</strong> — Performs deep root-cause analysis by exploring the codebase and tracing error paths. <em>Inputs:</em> classified incident ticket, codebase access, commit history, semantic memory. <em>Outputs:</em> root cause summary, relevant file list, context window for fix generation. <em>Decision logic:</em> follows call-stack traces, identifies recent commits touching failing paths, and cross-references with historical fixes.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Developer Agent</strong> — Generates targeted code patches and corresponding test cases. <em>Inputs:</em> root cause context from Investigator, file contents, project conventions. <em>Outputs:</em> code diff, test suite, self-review notes. <em>Decision logic:</em> applies minimal-diff strategy — prefers surgical edits over rewrites, and validates generated code against project lint and type rules before submission.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Ralph Wiggum (Stability Gate)</strong> — Validates every proposed fix through a comprehensive quality gate. <em>Inputs:</em> code diff and tests from Developer. <em>Outputs:</em> pass/fail verdict with detailed failure report. <em>Decision logic:</em> runs unit tests, lint checks, type verification, security scanning (OWASP top 10), and smoke tests. Rejects any fix that fails a single check and returns failure context to the Developer Agent for the next retry.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Creative Agent</strong> — Activated when the Developer Agent exhausts its retry budget without a passing fix. <em>Inputs:</em> accumulated failure context from previous attempts. <em>Outputs:</em> alternative solution strategies and unconventional approaches. <em>Decision logic:</em> breaks out of the local optimization loop by proposing fundamentally different solution paths — a different algorithm, a different module boundary, or a configuration-based fix instead of a code change.
        </div>
        <div class="stage-desc">
          <strong>Distiller Agent</strong> — Runs post-resolution to extract reusable knowledge from each completed incident. <em>Inputs:</em> full incident trace, root cause, fix diff, and test results. <em>Outputs:</em> condensed lesson entries written to semantic memory. <em>Decision logic:</em> identifies which parts of the investigation were novel versus redundant, and stores only the new knowledge that would accelerate future resolutions.
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 6: Ticket Lifecycle State Machine -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Ticket Lifecycle</h2>
      <p>Every incident follows a well-defined state machine from first alert to resolution. The ticket lifecycle ensures no issue falls through the cracks — every state transition is tracked, timed, and auditable.</p>

      <div class="diagram-container">
        <MermaidDiagram code={`stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> New: Alert Ingested
    New --> Triaged: Classified
    Triaged --> Investigating: Agent Assigned
    Investigating --> InDevelopment: Root Cause Found
    InDevelopment --> InReview: Fix Submitted
    InReview --> Deployed: All Checks Pass
    InReview --> InDevelopment: Checks Fail
    InDevelopment --> Escalated: Retry Limit Hit
    Escalated --> InDevelopment: Human Provides Guidance
    Deployed --> [*]: Resolved`} />
      </div>

      <p>Tickets move linearly through the pipeline under normal conditions. When the Stability Gate rejects a fix, the ticket loops back to In Development. If the retry budget is exhausted, the ticket escalates to a human engineer while remaining in the active queue. Once deployed, the ticket transitions to Resolved and feeds its findings back into semantic memory.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 7: Model Routing & Auto-Escalation -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Model Routing &amp; Escalation</h2>
      <p>SWE-Squad routes each task to the most cost-effective model capable of handling it. Simple classification runs on Haiku, investigation and patch generation use Sonnet, and complex architectural decisions invoke Opus.</p>

      <div class="diagram-container">
        <MermaidDiagram code={`flowchart TD
    Input[Incoming Incident] --> Classify{Complexity?}
    Classify -->|Simple| Haiku[Haiku<br/>~$0.25/1M tokens]
    Classify -->|Standard| Sonnet[Sonnet<br/>~$3.00/1M tokens]
    Classify -->|Complex| Opus[Opus<br/>~$15.00/1M tokens]
    Haiku --> Result{Pass?}
    Sonnet --> Result
    Opus --> Result
    Result -->|Yes| Deploy[Deploy Fix]
    Result -->|No + Retries Left| Upgrade{Upgrade Model?}
    Upgrade -->|Yes| NextModel[Next Tier Up]
    Upgrade -->|No| SameModel[Same Model + New Context]
    NextModel --> Result
    SameModel --> Result
    Result -->|No + Retries Exhausted| Escalate[Escalate to Human]`} />
      </div>

      <p>The auto-escalation path is equally important: if a model fails to produce a passing fix within its retry budget, the system first tries upgrading to the next model tier. If all tiers are exhausted, the incident escalates to a human engineer with the full diagnostic trace. This ensures every issue eventually reaches the right level of expertise — whether AI or human.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 8: Multi-Team Scoping -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Multi-Team Scoping</h2>
      <p>SWE-Squad supports multiple engineering teams within a single deployment. Each team is scoped to its own codebase boundaries, agent configurations, and escalation policies — while sharing a common memory store for cross-team learning.</p>

      <div class="diagram-container">
        <MermaidDiagram code={`flowchart TD
    subgraph Platform["SWE-Squad Platform"]
        Router[Team Router]
        Memory[Shared Memory Store]
        Router --> TeamA["Team Alpha<br/>Backend Services"]
        Router --> TeamB["Team Bravo<br/>Frontend & Mobile"]
        Router --> TeamC["Team Charlie<br/>Data Pipeline"]
        TeamA --> ScopeA["Scoped Codebase Access<br/>Service A, B, C"]
        TeamB --> ScopeB["Scoped Codebase Access<br/>Web, iOS, Android"]
        TeamC --> ScopeC["Scoped Codebase Access<br/>ETL, ML Pipeline"]
        ScopeA --> Memory
        ScopeB --> Memory
        ScopeC --> Memory
    end`} />
      </div>

      <p>The Team Router directs incoming alerts to the correct team based on service ownership metadata. Within each team, agents operate within strictly scoped codebase boundaries — a backend agent cannot access frontend repositories, and vice versa. However, the shared semantic memory store allows lessons learned by one team to benefit others. Cross-team incidents (e.g., an API change that breaks a frontend consumer) are detected by the Router and broadcast to all affected teams simultaneously.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Section 9: What Happens to a Log Line -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>What Happens to a Log Line</h2>
      <p>Follow a single error log line on its journey from ingestion to deployment.</p>

      <div class="narrative-step">
        <div class="step-number">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <Callout type="info" title="Ingestion">
            <p>A production service emits an error log line — perhaps a NullPointerException or a timeout stack trace. The Monitor stage ingests this line in real time alongside thousands of other log entries, normalizing its format and attaching metadata such as service name, timestamp, and environment.</p>
          </Callout>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="narrative-step">
        <div class="step-number">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <p>Pattern Detection scans the incoming stream against known anomaly signatures. The error line matches a threshold breach or a novel pattern, and the system flags it as anomalous, promoting it from a raw log entry to a structured alert.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="narrative-step">
        <div class="step-number">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <p>Triage takes over the alert. It classifies severity (critical, high, medium, low), checks whether an identical or similar issue is already being tracked, and deduplicates if necessary to avoid parallel agents working the same problem.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="narrative-step">
        <div class="step-number">4</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <p>The assignment step routes the incident to the right AI agent based on the service, language, and error category. Model routing ensures a fast Haiku-class model handles straightforward classification while a heavier Sonnet or Opus model is reserved for complex root-cause analysis.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="narrative-step">
        <div class="step-number">5</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <Callout type="tip" title="Deep Investigation">
            <p>The assigned agent enters the Investigate stage, exploring the codebase to locate the relevant files, tracing the error path through the call stack, and assembling a rich context window that includes surrounding code, recent commits, and any related historical fixes from the semantic memory store.</p>
          </Callout>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="narrative-step">
        <div class="step-number">6</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <p>In the Fix stage, the agent generates a targeted code patch, writes corresponding unit tests, and runs a self-review pass to catch syntax errors, off-by-one mistakes, or obvious logic flaws before submitting.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="narrative-step">
        <div class="step-number">7</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <Callout type="warning" title="Stability Gate">
            <p>The proposed fix is handed to the Stability Gate, which runs the full validation suite: unit tests, linting, type checking, security scanning, and smoke tests. If any check fails, the fix is rejected and the loop restarts. If all checks pass, the gate opens and the fix is cleared for deployment.</p>
          </Callout>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="narrative-step">
        <div class="step-number">8</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <Callout type="success" title="Deployed">
            <p>The validated fix is merged and deployed to production. The semantic memory store is updated with the new findings so that future encounters with the same pattern are resolved instantly — often without invoking a model at all.</p>
          </Callout>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  *,
  *::before,
  *::after {
    box-sizing: border-box;
  }

  body {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, 'Helvetica Neue', Arial, sans-serif;
    color: var(--color-text-primary);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .page {
    max-width: 48rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2rem 1.5rem 4rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    transition: color 0.15s;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    color: #2563eb;
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  .page-title {
    font-size: 2.25rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
    color: var(--color-text-primary);
  }

  .page-intro {
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin: 0 0 3rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* ---- Sections ---- */
  .section {
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
  }

  .section h2 {
    font-size: 1.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .section p {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }

  .section code {
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', 'Fira Mono', 'Roboto Mono', 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 0.875em;
    background: var(--color-bg-sidebar);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 0.125em 0.375em;
  }

  /* ---- Diagram container ---- */
  .diagram-container {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  /* ---- Stage descriptions ---- */
  .stage-descriptions {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin-top: 1.25rem;
  }

  .stage-desc {
    background: var(--color-bg-sidebar);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 0.5rem;
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .stage-desc strong {
    color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  /* ---- Narrative steps ---- */
  .narrative-step {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    align-items: flex-start;
  }

  .step-number {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 2.25rem;
    height: 2.25rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--color-accent);
    color: #ffffff;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    margin-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  .step-content {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .step-content p {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* ---- Responsive ---- */
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .page {
      padding: 1.5rem 1rem 3rem;
    }

    .page-title {
      font-size: 1.75rem;
    }

    .section h2 {
      font-size: 1.375rem;
    }

    .narrative-step {
      gap: 1rem;
    }

    .step-number {
      width: 2rem;
      height: 2rem;
      font-size: 0.8125rem;
    }
  }
</style>
